Phase 1 — Wire the risky pieces first

Install & render the editor

Add CKEditor 5 React (or TinyMCE if you prefer).

Make a temp page /app/audit-sandbox that just renders the editor.

Hardcode a sample HTML string (your crawler output).

Make sure onChange updates React state.

✅ Goal: “I can load HTML → edit → see new HTML in state.”

Create the rule registry skeleton

Make /lib/audit-rules/types.ts with AuditRule, AuditContext, AuditRuleResult.

Make /lib/audit-rules/index.ts that exports an empty ruleRegistry = {}.

✅ Goal: “I can import ruleRegistry and loop it without errors.”

Make 1 real rule file

e.g. /lib/audit-rules/seoTitleLength.ts

It should:

read ctx.meta.title

return status, evidence

define ui.sidebarSummary and ui.detailFields

Add it to ruleRegistry.

✅ Goal: “I can add a rule by making one file.”

Write the executor

Make /lib/audit/executeRules.ts

It should take (ctx) => {} and loop over ruleRegistry and return a dictionary of results.

For now, stub ctx with hardcoded HTML/meta.

✅ Goal: “I can run all rules in a loop and get results back.”

Phase 2 — Connect editor ↔ rules

Build the audit sandbox UI

Layout: left = rule list, right = editor.

State:

const [html, setHtml] = useState(sampleHtml);

const [ruleResults, setRuleResults] = useState({});

Add a button: “Run audit on this content”.

On click:

build ctx from current html (parse title, text)

call executeRules

save results in setRuleResults

✅ Goal: “I change content → run → see different rule results.”

Map rule results to UI

Left sidebar: list all rules from registry.

For each rule, show:

rule.meta.label

rule.ui.sidebarSummary(ruleResults[rule.key])

status color

Clicking a rule opens a side panel/modal with detailFields(...).

✅ Goal: “Rule files fully drive what UI shows.”

Highlight in editor (simple version)

Pick one rule (e.g. “ICP relevance”) and make it return a substring to highlight.

Before giving HTML to CKEditor, wrap that substring in <span class="audit-warn">...</span>.

✅ Goal: “Audit result can influence editor content.”

Phase 3 — Page/audit structure (still minimal UI)

Create data shapes for Website / Audit / AuditPage in code

Just TypeScript interfaces for now.

Create a dummy array of websites and audits in the sandbox page.

✅ Goal: “My rule system can receive a ctx that has url, pageType, icp.”

Add page-type awareness

In the sandbox page, let user pick: homepage / product / service / blog / pillar.

Pass that to executeRules.

Make one rule skip if pageType not applicable.

✅ Goal: “Rules can say ‘not applicable’.”

Phase 4 — Real fetching & context enrichment

Add real HTML fetch util

In /lib/audit/fetchHtml.ts write a server-side fetch that:

gets the URL

extracts <title>, <meta name=description>, <link rel=canonical>

Plug that into ctx instead of hardcoded HTML when URL is present.

✅ Goal: “I can audit a real URL, not just a pasted string.”

Add mutateContext support

Pick your schema rule and make it parse <script type="application/ld+json"> and write it to ctx.meta.schema.

In executor, after each rule, if rule has mutateContext, reassign ctx = mutateContext(...).

✅ Goal: “One rule can help the next.”

Phase 5 — Start shaping actual pages

Listing page (audits list)

Now that editor + rules work, make /app/audits:

list dummy audits

“Open” → /app/audits/[id] → loads sandbox-like UI with editor + rules

✅ Goal: “Navigation works; audit detail page uses the working components.”

Audit detail page shell

Header: audit name, website, ICP, status

2-column layout: left rule list, right editor

Reuse the sandbox logic

✅ Goal: “Real page uses the same rule engine.”

Phase 6 — Hardening / cleanup

Extract shared components

<RuleList />

<RuleDetail />

<AuditEditor /> (CKEditor wrapper)

Now your pages just assemble them.

✅ Goal: “Adding a new page is just composing components.”

Add loading / error states

If fetch fails, show warning item in the rule list.

If analyze throws, mark rule as fail with evidence.

✅ Goal: “Engine doesn’t crash on bad pages.”

Phase 7 — Optional but smart

Rule generator template

Create a code snippet/template for new rule files so you never start from scratch.

You can even make an internal route that POSTs rule metadata and scaffolds a file (later).

✅ Goal: “Adding rules stays fast.”

Order recap (short)

install editor → render → state works

create rule types + registry

add 1 rule file

write executor

build sandbox UI (sidebar + editor + run button)

display rule results

add simple highlight

add pageType + ICP to ctx

add real HTML fetch

create audits list/detail pages

That will get you from “nothing” to “I can load a real page and run multiple modular rules on it, showing results next to an editor” without getting stuck on lower-risk markup work.